  "evidence_entities": [
    {
      "id": "PMC_extracted:abstract:1:llm",
      "class": "Evidence",
      "entity_id": null,
      "paper_id": "PMC_extracted",
      "text_span_id": "abstract_1",
      "text": "Of all congenital adrenal hyperplasia (CAH), 95% to 99% is 21-hydroxylase deficiency (21OHD), an autosomal recessive disease. 21OHD is due to an insufficiency of 21-hydroxylase enzyme, which is encoded by the CYP21A2 gene and involved in cortisol and aldosterone production.",
      "confidence": 0.95,
      "extraction_method": "llm",
      "study_type": "Review",
      "eco_type": null,
      "source": "extracted"
    },
    {
      "id": "PMC_extracted:introduction:1:llm",
      "class": "Evidence",
      "entity_id": null,
      "paper_id": "PMC_extracted",
      "text_span_id": "introduction_1",
      "text": "The predominant enzyme deficiency that accounts for 95% to 99% of all CAH cases is 21-hydroxylase deficiency (21OHD). The 21OH enzyme converts 17\u03b1-hydroxyprogesterone to 11-deoxycortisol and progesterone to deoxycorticosterone.",
      "confidence": 0.95,
      "extraction_method": "llm",
      "study_type": "Review",
      "eco_type": null,
      "source": "extracted"
    },
    {
      "id": "PMC_extracted:introduction:2:llm",
      "class": "Evidence",
      "entity_id": null,
      "paper_id": "PMC_extracted",
      "text_span_id": "introduction_2",
      "text": "21OHD comprises 2 groups, the classic and nonclassic (NC) form. Classic 21OHD is further divided into salt-wasting (SW) (cortisol and aldosterone deficiency) and simple virilizing (SV) phenotype (cortisol and milder aldosterone deficiency).",
      "confidence": 0.95,
      "extraction_method": "llm",
      "study_type": "Review",
      "eco_type": null,
      "source": "extracted"
    },
    {
      "id": "PMC_extracted:introduction:3:llm",
      "class": "Evidence",
      "entity_id": null,
      "paper_id": "PMC_extracted",
      "text_span_id": "introduction_3",
      "text": "The serum 17\u03b1-hydroxyprogesterone (17OHP) concentration is utilized as the principal marker for 21OHD, since CAH due to 21OHD is detected in NBS programs using 17OHP concentration measurements in dried blood spots.",
      "confidence": 0.95,
      "extraction_method": "llm",
      "study_type": "Review",
      "eco_type": null,
      "source": "extracted"
    },
    {
      "id": "PMC_extracted:genetics:1:llm",
      "class": "Evidence",
      "entity_id": null,
      "paper_id": "PMC_extracted",
      "text_span_id": "genetics_1",
      "text": "Over 95% of deleterious variants leading to 21OHD are attributable to intergenic recombination events where microconversions, consisting in the transfer to CYP21A2 of deleterious variants usually present in the CYP21A1P pseudogene, represent 70% to 75%.",
      "confidence": 0.95,
      "extraction_method": "llm",
      "study_type": "Review",
      "eco_type": null,
      "source": "extracted"
    },
    {
      "id": "PMC_extracted:genetics:2:llm",
      "class": "Evidence",
      "entity_id": null,
      "paper_id": "PMC_extracted",
      "text_span_id": "genetics_2",
      "text": "The genetic cause of CAH-X syndrome is a recombination event between TNXB and its pseudogene TNXA. The resulting 30 kb deletion includes the entire CYP21A2 gene sequence and part of the TNXB gene and produces a chimeric TNXA/TNXB gene (CAH-X chimera).",
      "confidence": 0.95,
      "extraction_method": "llm",
      "study_type": "Review",
      "eco_type": null,
      "source": "extracted"
    },
    {
      "id": "PMC_extracted:genetics:3:llm",
      "class": "Evidence",
      "entity_id": null,
      "paper_id": "PMC_extracted",
      "text_span_id": "genetics_3",
      "text": "The functional consequence of this rearrangement is the complete absence of the 21OH enzyme and the deficiency of tenascin-X, while the resulting phenotype is a hypermobility form of Ehlers-Danlos syndrome (EDS).",
      "confidence": 0.95,
      "extraction_method": "llm",
      "study_type": "Review",
      "eco_type": null,
      "source": "extracted"
    },
    {
      "id": "PMC_extracted:treatment:1:llm",
      "class": "Evidence",
      "entity_id": null,
      "paper_id": "PMC_extracted",
      "text_span_id": "treatment_1",
      "text": "The main therapies in CAH are glucocorticoids to replace the deficiency and normalize the adrenal androgens and mineralocorticoids, compulsory in SW CAH but often also used in SV CAH.",
      "confidence": 0.95,
      "extraction_method": "llm",
      "study_type": "Review",
      "eco_type": null,
      "source": "extracted"
    },
    {
      "id": "PMC_extracted:treatment:2:llm",
      "class": "Evidence",
      "entity_id": null,
      "paper_id": "PMC_extracted",
      "text_span_id": "treatment_2",
      "text": "Mineralocorticoids, in the form of fludrocortisone, are particularly important prior to (since they may induce ovulation) and during pregnancy in patients with SW CAH but may also be used in those with SV CAH.",
      "confidence": 0.95,
      "extraction_method": "llm",
      "study_type": "Review",
      "eco_type": null,
      "source": "extracted"
    }
  ],
